With reference to the generated plots for 20-epoch run:
Immediate Convergence:
The most prominent feature of this run is that validation accuracy starts at approximately 1.0 (100%) on Epoch 1 and remains completely flat.
Training accuracy catches up by Epoch 2. This proves your hypothesis: the model did not need to spend time learning basic shapes or edges.

Feature Extraction Efficacy:
Because MobileNetV2 was pre-trained on ImageNet, it already possessed highly optimized feature maps for identifying natural objects.
The only parameters being trained were the small custom classification head.
It took precisely one pass over the data to map those pre-learned features to your specific "Apple," "Orange," and "Banana" labels.

Absence of Overfitting:
Both training and validation loss drop to near-zero and remain tightly coupled throughout the 20 epochs.
There is no divergence, meaning the frozen base model successfully prevented the network from memorizing the training dataset.

Final Conclusion:
The transfer learning experiment drastically outperformed the custom-built CNN.
While the custom model with data augmentation required roughly 15-20 epochs to stabilize above 95% accuracy,
the pre-trained MobileNetV2 architecture achieved near-perfect accuracy and stabilization by Epoch 2,
proving the efficiency of leveraging pre-learned feature extractors for standard classification tasks.
